# 🎣 Phishing Email Detector

A multi-layer analysis engine for detecting phishing emails from `.eml` files. No external API required for core functionality.

## What It Analyzes

| Layer | What It Detects |
|---|---|
| **Sender Analysis** | Display name spoofing, domain lookalikes, Reply-To hijacking, Return-Path mismatch |
| **Authentication (SPF/DKIM/DMARC)** | Email authentication failures — the most reliable phishing signal |
| **URL Inspection** | IP-based URLs, URL shorteners, suspicious TLDs, misleading links, brand-in-subdomain |
| **Subject Analysis** | Urgency patterns, excessive punctuation, spoofed reply chains |
| **Body Content** | Urgency keywords, credential harvesting language, hidden forms, password fields |
| **Attachment Check** | Flags dangerous extensions (.exe, .js, .docm, macro files, etc.) |
| **Routing Analysis** | Traces hop chain, detects IP-only senders, unusual routing paths |
| **Risk Scoring** | Evidence-weighted 0–100 score with full reasoning |

## Installation

```bash
# No dependencies required — uses only Python stdlib
python phishing_detector.py suspicious.eml

# Optional: install requests for future VT integration
pip install requests
```

## Usage

```bash
# Analyze a single email
python phishing_detector.py suspicious.eml

# Save report to JSON
python phishing_detector.py email.eml --output report.json

# Batch analyze a directory
python phishing_detector.py ./email_samples/ --batch
```

## How to Get .eml Files

| Email Client | How to Export |
|---|---|
| **Gmail** | More → Download Message |
| **Outlook** | File → Save As → .msg (convert with `msgconvert` to .eml) |
| **Thunderbird** | Save As → .eml |
| **Command line** | `curl -u user:pass imaps://mail.example.com/INBOX/1 > email.eml` |

## Sample Output

```
============================================================
  PHISHING ANALYSIS SUMMARY
============================================================
  File:    phish_paypal.eml
  Subject: URGENT: Your PayPal account has been limited!

  RISK SCORE: 87/100
  VERDICT:    HIGH RISK — Likely Phishing

  Evidence:
    • SPF FAIL — sender may not be who they claim
    • DKIM not configured on sender domain
    • Display name spoof: claims to be 'PayPal Security' but sent from updates.srv-notify.xyz
    • Reply-To domain differs from From domain (response hijacking)
    • Risky URL (account-verify.xyz): IP address used instead of domain
    • 2 misleading link(s) — visible text differs from actual URL
    • HTML form with password input field(s) — credential harvester
    • 6 urgency keyword(s) in body
============================================================
```

## Key Concepts to Study

- **SPF (Sender Policy Framework)** — DNS TXT records declaring authorized sending servers. `spf=fail` means the email came from an unauthorized server.
- **DKIM (DomainKeys Identified Mail)** — Cryptographic signature in email headers. Validates message integrity and sender identity.
- **DMARC** — Policy layer on top of SPF/DKIM. Tells receivers what to do when checks fail (none/quarantine/reject).
- **Email Header Analysis** — Learn to read raw headers. The `Received:` chain tells you where an email really came from.
- **Homograph Attacks** — Unicode lookalike characters (е vs e, а vs a) in domains.

## Extending This Project

- Add integration with [PhishTank API](https://phishtank.org) for URL reputation
- Add Unicode/Punycode homograph detection
- Build a bulk training dataset and train a machine learning classifier
- Create a real-time Gmail/Outlook plugin using IMAP
- Add WHOIS lookups to check domain registration age (new domains = higher risk)

